{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-04-20T18:11:59.355057+00:00", "modified": "2026-04-20T18:12:00.021502+00:00", "id": 19668268, "conceptrecid": "19668267", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19668268", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.19668267", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19668268", "metadata": {"title": "Quantifying biodiversity: procedures and pitfalls in the measurement and comparison of species richness", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19668268", "publication_date": "2001", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Species richness is a fundamental measurement of community and regional diversity, and it underlies many ecological models and conservation strategies. In spite of its importance, ecologists have not always appreciated the effects of abundance and sampling effort on richness measures and comparisons. We survey a series of common pitfalls in quantifying and comparing taxon richness. These pitfalls can be largely avoided by using accumulation and rarefaction curves, which may be based on either individuals or samples. These taxon sampling curves contain the basic information for valid richness comparisons, including category\u00b1subcategory ratios (species-to-genus and species-toindividual ratios). Rarefaction methods \u00b1 both sample-based and individual-based \u00b1 allow for meaningful standardization and comparison of datasets. Standardizing data sets by area or sampling effort may produce very different results compared to standardizing by number of individuals collected, and it is not always clear which measure of diversity is more appropriate. Asymptotic richness estimators provide lower-bound estimates for taxon-rich groups such as tropical arthropods, in which observed richness rarely reaches an asymptote, despite intensive sampling. Recent examples of diversity studies of tropical trees, stream invertebrates, and herbaceous plants emphasize the importance of carefully quantifying species richness using taxon sampling curves.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Gotelli, Nicholas J.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Colwell, Robert K.", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/ff9e9881798d6c2ec70218f6ff5e8173", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/59b2cf21bc77c3aa0d1fc4ec01f112640f6ffaa21638856dc8b3842a95af8919", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/JW2P27MZ", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/JW2P27MZ", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/991c4c7088e22b4a9bc0a858cb6fe28b!/b388149-390648", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/0157e8ec3f1f8eb877e7b6cd6fde26bc", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "custom": {"dwc:class": ["Mammalia"], "dwc:kingdom": ["Animalia"], "dwc:order": ["Chiroptera"], "dwc:phylum": ["Chordata"]}, "resource_type": {"title": "Journal article", "type": "publication", "subtype": "article"}, "journal": {"issue": "4", "pages": "379-391", "title": "Ecology Letters", "volume": "4"}, "alternate_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/ff9e9881798d6c2ec70218f6ff5e8173"}, {"identifier": "urn:lsid:zotero.org:groups:5435545:items:JW2P27MZ"}, {"identifier": "10.1046/j.1461-0248.2001.00230.x"}], "communities": [{"id": "biosyslit"}, {"id": "batlit"}], "relations": {"version": [{"index": 0, "is_last": true, "parent": {"pid_type": "recid", "pid_value": "19668267"}}]}}, "title": "Quantifying biodiversity: procedures and pitfalls in the measurement and comparison of species richness", "links": {"self": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/19668268", "self_html"